TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Panel Study of Coping with Involuntary Job Loss
AU  - Kinicki, Angelo J.
AU  - Prussia, Gregory E.
AU  - McKee‐Ryan, Frances M.
Y1  - 2000/02/01
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/1556388
DO  - 10.5465/1556388
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 90
EP  - 100
VL  - 43
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - We examined the role of the quality of reemployment in the process of coping with job loss using a panel design and a four?month interval for 100 displaced workers. The dynamic process of coping with job loss changed between the anticipatory and outcome stages. The quality of reemployment played a key role, interacting with time in such a way that satisfactorily reemployed workers experienced reduced economic discrepancies and replenished coping resources. The dissatisfactorily reemployed and the unemployed continued to experience negative effects.
AB  - We examined the role of the quality of reemployment in the process of coping with job loss using a panel design and a four?month interval for 100 displaced workers. The dynamic process of coping with job loss changed between the anticipatory and outcome stages. The quality of reemployment played a key role, interacting with time in such a way that satisfactorily reemployed workers experienced reduced economic discrepancies and replenished coping resources. The dissatisfactorily reemployed and the unemployed continued to experience negative effects.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/1556388
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/1556388
