TY  - JOUR
T1  - Network Destruction: The Structural Implications of Downsizing
AU  - Shah, Priti Pradhan
Y1  - 2000/02/01
PY  - 2000
DA  - 2000/02/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/1556389
DO  - 10.5465/1556389
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 101
EP  - 112
VL  - 43
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Downsizing disrupts existing social networks in organizations. Layoff survivors' reactions to losses of both friends and coworkers in similar structural positions (structural equivalents) are examined here. A field study conducted in a consumer electronics firm revealed negative reactions to the loss of friends and positive reactions to the loss of coworkers in similar structural positions. The loss of friends weakened survivors' network centrality, but the loss of structural equivalents benefited network position and increased satisfaction with promotion opportunities.
AB  - Downsizing disrupts existing social networks in organizations. Layoff survivors' reactions to losses of both friends and coworkers in similar structural positions (structural equivalents) are examined here. A field study conducted in a consumer electronics firm revealed negative reactions to the loss of friends and positive reactions to the loss of coworkers in similar structural positions. The loss of friends weakened survivors' network centrality, but the loss of structural equivalents benefited network position and increased satisfaction with promotion opportunities.
